    type: string
    description: >-
      Duration of the customer non-solicitation restriction, measured from the
      end of employment. This is a surviving covenant under the Minnesota
      Noncompetition Agreement Act; keep it a finite, relationship-protective
      term so the clause does not function as a banned restraint on competition.
    display_label: Customer Non-Solicitation Duration
    default: 12 months
    rationale_source: benchmark
    benchmark_ref: restrictive-covenant/customer-non-solicit-duration
    section: Customer Non-Solicitation
    default_value_rationale: >-
      12 months is the most common customer non-solicit term in benchmarked,
      publicly-filed employee agreements, edging out 24 months by only a narrow
      margin. Minnesota law permits customer-solicitation restrictions only when
      they remain relationship-protective rather than operating as a substitute
      restraint on competition, so counsel should shorten or narrow the term if
      the protected relationships do not justify a full year.
  - name: covered_customer_period
    type: string
    description: >-
      Look-back window before termination used to bound the class of Covered
      Customers to those the employee actually dealt with or had responsibility
      for. The Minnesota Noncompetition Agreement Act leaves customer
      non-solicits lawful, but an all-customers class pushes the clause toward a
      banned functional non-compete, so the class is tied to a stated look-back
      window.
    display_label: Covered Customer Look-Back
    default: 12 months
    section: Customer Non-Solicitation
    rationale_source: editorial
    default_value_rationale: >-
      12 months is a conservative look-back window that limits Covered Customers
      to recent, relationship-based contacts. Minnesota law does not set this
      number, so counsel should adjust it to the employee's actual customer
      responsibilities and the relationships being protected.
  - name: employee_nonsolicit_duration
    type: string
    description: >-
      Duration of the employee non-solicitation (no-poach) restriction, measured
      from the end of employment. This is a surviving covenant under the
      Minnesota Noncompetition Agreement Act; keep it finite and
      workforce-relationship-protective, not a substitute restraint on the
      employee's own work.
    display_label: Employee Non-Solicitation Duration
    default: 24 months
    section: Employee Non-Solicitation
    rationale_source: benchmark
    benchmark_ref: restrictive-covenant/employee-non-solicit-duration
    default_value_rationale: >-
      24 months matches the modal employee non-solicit term observed in
      benchmarked, publicly-filed employee agreements; 12 months is the common
      lighter alternative. Minnesota law does not set a fixed duration, so
      counsel should size the period to the workforce relationships being
      protected and avoid using it as a substitute restraint on the employee's
      own work.
  - name: covered_employee_period
    type: string
    description: >-
      Look-back window before termination used to bound the class of Covered
      Employees to colleagues the employee actually worked with or supervised. A
      workforce-wide class adds nothing protective and pushes a lawful no-poach
      toward the functional-non-compete line the statute polices by effect.
    display_label: Covered Employee Look-Back
    default: 12 months
    section: Employee Non-Solicitation
omitted_clauses: drop
